<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Mastering L*a*b* Adjustments in RawTherapee</title>
    <script src="https://cdn.tailwindcss.com"></script>
    <style>
        body { font-family: 'Inter', system-ui, -apple-system, sans-serif; }
        .gradient-bg { background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1a1a1a 0%, #2d2d2d 100%); }
        .tool-card { transition: transform 0.2s; }
        .tool-card:hover { transform: translateY(-4px); }
    </style>
</head>
<body class="bg-gray-50 text-gray-900">

    <!-- Header -->
    <header class="gradient-bg text-white py-16 px-6 text-center">
        <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold mb-4">L*a*b* Adjustments</h1>
        <p class="text-xl text-gray-300 max-w-2xl mx-auto">The secret weapon of professional RawTherapee workflows for surgical control over color and light.</p>
    </header>

    <main class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6 py-12">
        
        <!-- Why L*a*b* Section -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6 flex items-center">
                <span class="bg-blue-600 text-white w-8 h-8 rounded-full inline-flex items-center justify-center mr-3 text-lg">?</span>
                Why Edit in L*a*b* instead of RGB?
            </h2>
            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 bg-white p-8 rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-gray-100">
                <div>
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3 text-blue-700">The Power of Separation</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                        In the RGB space, <strong>Lightness</strong> and <strong>Color</strong> are inextricably linked. If you increase the Red channel, you are simultaneously increasing the brightness of the reds. This often leads to unwanted color shifts or "crunchy" highlights when trying to adjust exposure.
                    </p>
                    <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
                        The L*a*b* model separates <strong>Luminosity (L)</strong> entirely from the color channels (a* and b*). This allows you to boost contrast or exposure without distorting the saturation or hue of your image.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-gray-50 p-6 rounded-xl border border-gray-200">
                    <ul class="space-y-4">
                        <li class="flex items-start">
                            <span class="text-green-500 font-bold mr-2">✓</span>
                            <span><strong>No Color Shifts:</strong> Adjust brightness without turning your blues into cyans.</span>
                        </li>
                        <li class="flex items-start">
                            <span class="text-green-500 font-bold mr-2">✓</span>
                            <span><strong>Perceptual Accuracy:</strong> The space is designed to mimic how humans actually see color.</span>
                        </li>
                        <li class="flex items-start">
                            <span class="text-green-500 font-bold mr-2">✓</span>
                            <span><strong>Munsell Correction:</strong> Uses specialized math to keep skin tones looking natural even under heavy edits.</span>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Tool Breakdown -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-8">The Adjustment Toolkit</h2>
            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
                
                <!-- LH -->
                <div class="tool-card bg-white p-6 rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-gray-100">
                    <div class="text-xs font-bold text-blue-500 uppercase mb-2">Lightness vs Hue</div>
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-3">LH</h3>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Brighten or darken specific colors. Perfect for making a blue sky deeper or a yellow flower glow against dark grass.</p>
                </div>

                <!-- CH -->
                <div class="tool-card bg-white p-6 rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-gray-100">
                    <div class="text-xs font-bold text-pink-500 uppercase mb-2">Chroma vs Hue</div>
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-3">CH</h3>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Saturate or desaturate specific hues. Vivid up the greens in a forest without touching the skin tones of people in the frame.</p>
                </div>

                <!-- HH -->
                <div class="tool-card bg-white p-6 rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-gray-100">
                    <div class="text-xs font-bold text-purple-500 uppercase mb-2">Hue vs Hue</div>
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-3">HH</h3>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Shift one color toward another. Useful for correcting slight tints or artistic color grading (e.g., shifting greens toward autumn oranges).</p>
                </div>

                <!-- CC -->
                <div class="tool-card bg-white p-6 rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-gray-100">
                    <div class="text-xs font-bold text-orange-500 uppercase mb-2">Chroma vs Chroma</div>
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-3">CC</h3>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Selective saturation. Boost muted colors while protecting already-vibrant areas from clipping or becoming "neon."</p>
                </div>

                <!-- LC -->
                <div class="tool-card bg-white p-6 rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-gray-100">
                    <div class="text-xs font-bold text-teal-500 uppercase mb-2">Lightness vs Chroma</div>
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-3">LC</h3>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Adjust brightness based on color intensity. Used frequently to hide skin blemishes by darkening high-chroma areas of the face.</p>
                </div>

                <!-- CL -->
                <div class="tool-card bg-white p-6 rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-gray-100">
                    <div class="text-xs font-bold text-red-500 uppercase mb-2">Chroma vs Lightness</div>
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-3">CL</h3>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Control saturation in shadows and highlights. Desaturate noisy shadows for a cleaner look while keeping midtones colorful.</p>
                </div>

            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Pro Tips -->
        <section class="bg-blue-900 text-white p-8 md:p-12 rounded-3xl">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-6">Expert Configuration</h2>
            <div class="space-y-6">
                <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                    <div class="p-2 bg-blue-800 rounded-lg">⚙️</div>
                    <div>
                        <h4 class="font-bold">MTH Cell (Avoid Color Shift)</h4>
                        <p class="text-blue-200 text-sm">Leave this on the default setting for 99% of cases. It ensures that saturation boosts don't cause hues to shift unnaturally.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                    <div class="p-2 bg-blue-800 rounded-lg">👤</div>
                    <div>
                        <h4 class="font-bold">Restrict LC to Red & Skin Tones</h4>
                        <p class="text-blue-200 text-sm">When checked, the LC tool only affects skin-like colors, preventing your background from changing while you retouch a portrait.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                    <div class="p-2 bg-blue-800 rounded-lg">📈</div>
                    <div>
                        <h4 class="font-bold">Tin Pan Alley</h4>
                        <p class="text-blue-200 text-sm">The three sliders at the top (Lightness, Contrast, Chromaticity) are global "coarse" adjustments. Use them for the overall feel, then dive into the curves for surgical precision.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

    </main>

    <footer class="text-center py-12 border-t border-gray-200 text-gray-500 text-sm">
        <p>Created for RawTherapee users seeking professional color control.</p>
    </footer>

</body>
</html>
